greatest-hits charts. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Soundscan</ENAMEX> gets its <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">numbers</ENAMEX> from a scanning device
installed at checkout <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">counters</ENAMEX> at <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">more than 85 percent</NUMEX> of all music <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">outlets</ENAMEX> in
<ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">America</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bookscan</ENAMEX> is trying to put a similar gizmo into <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">bookstores</ENAMEX>. So far, it
hasn't caught on. Unlike <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Soundscan</ENAMEX>, which swept swiftly through the music
business after it was introduced, when <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bookscan</ENAMEX> was unveiled <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>, it was
dismissed by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Association of Publishers</ENAMEX>, whose official line on it
